3. QUICK START
================================================================================

3.1 Prepare Input Files

Place the following in your working directory:

    link.dat              # Crosslink data file
    protein_A.pdb         # PDB file for protein A
    protein_B.pdb         # PDB file for protein B
    [additional .pdb files for all proteins in link.dat]

3.2 Generate Configuration File

    python x-pie-modeling.py

On first run, this creates x-pie.cfg and exits. Edit the file to set your
XPLOR paths (see Section 7).

3.3 Run the Pipeline

Interactive mode (recommended for first-time users):

    python x-pie-modeling.py

Batch mode (fully automatic):

    python x-pie-modeling.py --config x-pie.cfg

3.4 Review Outputs

Check the generated models in output/ and select the best structures based
on restraint violation scores (Calc_*.pdb.viols).


================================================================================
4. INPUT FILES
================================================================================

4.1 Crosslink File (link.dat)

Format: whitespace-separated text, one crosslink per line, four columns:

    Protein_A  Residue_Number_A  Protein_B  Residue_Number_B

Example:
    actin   328   cofilin   144
    actin   326   cofilin   144
    actin    50   cofilin    22

Requirements:
- Protein names must match PDB filenames (case-sensitive)
- Residue numbers must correspond to crosslinked residues
- Each protein in link.dat must have a corresponding <protein_name>.pdb
- If the crosslinked residue is not lysine (lacking an NZ atom), for example when the crosslink occurs at the protein N-terminus, the program automatically uses the backbone N atom of the corresponding crosslinked residue as the target for computational analysis.

4.2 PDB Files

- One PDB file per protein named exactly as in link.dat
- Crosslinked residues must contain complete side chains with NZ atoms
- Missing residues at non-crosslinked sites are acceptable

Important:
Since sampling is performed in all-atom mode with NZ atom distances as
restraints by default, please ensure that crosslinked residues have complete
side chains in the initial PDB structures before running X-PIE. Missing
residues at non-crosslinked sites do not affect the calculation.


================================================================================
5. WORKFLOW
================================================================================

Step 1: Crosslink Analysis
--------------------------
Input:  link.dat, *.pdb
Output: interface-define/

The script partitions each protein into structural domains, identifies
disordered linker regions, and clusters crosslink sites into spatially
distinct interaction interfaces. A schematic diagram is generated for visual
inspection.

Files generated:
    <protein>_domains.txt     Domain residue ranges
    <protein>_linker.txt      Long disordered/linker regions
    <protein>_loop.txt        Short flexible loops (if enabled)
    <A>_<B>_clusters.txt      Crosslink interface clusters
    <A>_<B>_schematic.png     Visualization diagram

In interactive mode, the pipeline pauses after this step for manual review.
Edit any of the above files if needed before continuing.

Step 2: Input File Generation
-----------------------------
Input:  interface-define/*
Output: input/xlms.tbl, refine.py

Generates distance restraints (xlms.tbl) and the XPLOR control script
(refine.py) that drives structure calculation.

In interactive mode, the pipeline pauses for review of xlms.tbl and refine.py.

Step 3: PDB/PSF Preparation
---------------------------
Input:  *.pdb (from pdb_dir)
Output: input/*-prepare.pdb, input/*-prepare.psf

Cleans PDB files, generates PSF topology files, rebuilds hydrogen atoms,
and performs short energy minimization. This step runs XPLOR twice per
protein and may take several minutes.

Step 4: Conformational Sampling
-------------------------------
Command: xplor -py refine.py -smp <num_cores>

Input:  refine.py, input/*
Output: output/Calc_*.pdb, output/Calc_*.pdb.viols

Runs simulated annealing to generate structural models satisfying the
crosslink distance restraints while respecting domain rigid-body constraints.

In the scripts/ folder, we provide the `analyze_structures.py` script for structural analysis. 
After inputting the path to the structures, the number of structures to be analyzed, and reference PDB structure information (if available), the script automatically calculates the total energy of these structures and ranks them. 
It selects structures with the lowest energy and no significant atomic clashes, and computes RMSD values reflecting structural convergence. 
If a reference structure is provided, the script also calculates the RMSD values of these structures relative to the reference structure.

